The paper proposes an end-to-end speaker verification system based on neural networks and a loss function. This could fall under several sub-categories, but the most likely ones are speech and natural language processing (cs.CL), machine learning (cs.LG), computer vision (cs.CV), and sound (cs.SD). The paper specifically mentions using a ResNet architecture to extract features from utterances, which is commonly used in computer vision tasks. Additionally, the large-margin Gaussian Mixture loss function used in the paper is a machine learning technique. Finally, the paper deals with speaker verification, which is a sound-related task.
